that, other than when Warren bought a big chunk of Apple=E2=80=94and made a=
 fortune on it=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s been a pretty dry well in term=
s of private companies that Berkshire has purchased.=E2=80=9D (Of course Ap=
ple was a public company when Buffett bought the Apple stock, but anyway.) =
Bill must have been listening to himself, because he was quick to add, =E2=
=80=9CLove the man. [He=E2=80=99s] been an amazing inspiration. I think Ber=
kshire owns some incredible businesses.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Bill noted that h=
e himself had bought Berkshire Hathaway
stock around the onset of the Covid pandemic, and sold the stock <em>at a l=
oss</em>=E2=80=94making him one of the few supposedly brilliant people to l=
ose money on it. (His mistake was selling way too soon, not unlike when he =
bought and sold Netflix in 2022, perfecting a loss of $400 million along th=
e way, on a company that has seen its market valuation quadruple since then=
=2E If Bill had held on to Netflix he w=
ould have made a fortune.)<br/><br/>Bi=
ll was now in deep waters, without a life vest. He told
Boyar that he hopes Warren lives forever=E2=80=94but then noted that the ne=
xt generation of leaders at Berkshire is =E2=80=9Cmuch more disciplined=E2=
=80=9D and that there=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ca lot of value to be extracted in =
running the businesses that Berkshire owns better.=E2=80=9D In case anyone =
missed Bill implying that perhaps he might be able to run Berkshire better =
than Warren, he added that his mentor was =E2=80=9Creluctant to, in any way=
, get involved in fixing companies=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Chas C.E.O.s that h=
e probably should have replaced years ago.=E2=80=9D</p>
