ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;">At this point, Bill was on a roll, and decided to tell Boyar abou=
t yet
<em>another</em> time Warren ignored Bill=E2=80=99s investment advice and l=
ost a chance to make a bundle. You may recall that Bill struck platinum bet=
ting that the Covid pandemic would freak out the bond market so much that t=
he Federal Reserve would come to its rescue, much as it did during the 2008=
 financial crisis. Bill was proven right, turning a $27 million investment =
in credit default swaps into <em>$3.5 billion</em> in about three weeks=E2=
=80=94inarguably one of the greatest trades of all time. After
buying and selling the credit default swaps, Bill funneled his $2.5 billion=
 of winnings into his stock portfolio, including both Hilton and Lowe=E2=80=
=99s, and made another $1 billion in profit. <br/><br/>Bill told Boyar that=
 he tried to interest Buffett in the same trade at the time, specifically t=
he part about buying stocks in and around March 2020, in anticipation that =
the Fed would backstop the bond market. =E2=80=9CI actually reached out to =
Buffett in February of 2020 expressing my concern about Covid,=E2=80=9D he
said. =E2=80=9CHe dismissed my concerns. =E2=80=A6 I thought Buffett would =
be taking advantage of this amazing opportunity to buy stocks. And he was f=
rozen. The opportunities had expanded dramatically in March of 2020, and we=
 said, =E2=80=98You know what? We can sell Berkshire at a loss,=E2=80=99 wh=
ich we did. We probably lost more money on Berkshire Hathaway, ironically, =
than almost anyone else, because of the scale of our investment.=E2=80=9D A=
nd with that, Bill ended his <em>All About Eve</em>-like ruminations on the=
 Oracle of
Omaha.<br/><br/>A few days after the podcast dropped, Bill posted on X that=
, =E2=80=9Cas they sadly often do,=E2=80=9D the =E2=80=9Cmedia=E2=80=9D had=
 =E2=80=9Ctwisted=E2=80=9D his words about Buffett to make it seem that Bil=
l had taken =E2=80=9Ca shot=E2=80=9D at him. Bill insisted that he wasn=E2=
=80=99t being critical of Warren=E2=80=94or certainly didn=E2=80=99t <em>in=
tend</em> to be critical of Warren=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cwho has been an extreme=
ly important hero for me and an unofficial mentor.=E2=80=9D He added that w=
hat he=E2=80=99d said about Warren=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cprice discipline=E2=
=80=9D wasn=E2=80=99t meant as =E2=80=9Ca criticism,=E2=80=9D but rather,
=E2=80=9Cjust an observation.=E2=80=9D As for why he sold his stake in Berk=
shire during the pandemic, =E2=80=9CWe found better things to do with our c=
apital,=E2=80=9D Bill explained.<br/><br/>He also added some additional con=
text to his prediction that the next generation at Berkshire, such as <stro=
ng>Greg Abel</strong>, the designated C.E.O.-in-waiting, would be more aggr=
essive in managing businesses in the firm=E2=80=99s portfolio. =E2=80=9CI d=
on=E2=80=99t think he likes firing C.E.O.s,=E2=80=9D Bill wrote about Warre=
n. =E2=80=9CHe has built many-decade
relationships with his C.E.O.s and the families that run businesses that he=
 has acquired. He values those relationships over the incremental economics=
 that could be extracted if a better operator were running those businesses=
=2E=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>On X, Bill went=20=
on to say that Boyar=E2=80=99s edit of=
 the interview lumped together his comments about Buffett=E2=80=94=E2=80=9C=
which may have changed, perhaps subtly, the impression the original would h=
ave conveyed. I believe that podcasts should be largely unedited real time
recordings of what was said, =E2=80=A6 so I was surprised when I read the t=
ranscript, in that it did not match my recollection of how the interview tr=
anspired, which may have contributed to any misimpressions.=E2=80=9D<br/><b=
r/>Bill asked Boyar to reissue the podcast in its original form, which Boya=
r subsequently did. For his part, Boyar wrote on X that =E2=80=9Cno substan=
tive changes=E2=80=9D were made to the interview, and that he=E2=80=99d com=
municated the changes to Bill and his team before releasing the podcast. =
=E2=80=9CIntegrity is
everything,=E2=80=9D Boyar wrote in response, =E2=80=9Cand I would never al=
ter an interview in a way that misrepresents a guest=E2=80=99s words.=E2=80=
=9D<br/><br/>When I reached out to Boyar to elaborate on the kerfuffle, he =
responded with a statement describing Bill=E2=80=99s analysis as both fair =
and factual. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t see why pointing out Buffett=E2=80=99=
s mistakes in a respectful manner should be considered blasphemy,=E2=80=9D =
he said. =E2=80=9CThe bottom line is that Buffett is the GOAT of investing,=
 but like all investors, he makes mistakes.=E2=80=9D He
continued: =E2=80=9CBuffett has always maintained that in investing, there =
are no called strikes=E2=80=94you don=E2=80=99t have to swing at every pitc=
h. And he=E2=80=99s still practicing what he preached his entire career, ch=
oosing his spots carefully and prioritizing avoiding mistakes over chasing =
every opportunity.=E2=80=9D On that, at least, I think we all can agree, ri=
ght Bill?</p></div>
